00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:05.920
- Anything else?
- Yep ― what I didn't find.

237
00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:09.320
The bottle the dead guy
was drinking from.

238
00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:15.120
- So whoever used this glass likely
took the bottle from the room. Why?

239
00:17:15.360 --> 00:17:17.720
- Because of the poison. I guess.

240
00:17:17.720 --> 00:17:19.720
- OK.

241
00:17:21.240 --> 00:17:26.840
Guess who I just saw at the pub?
Having lunch and looking
quite settled.

242
00:17:26.840 --> 00:17:28.680
- Shaylah.

243
00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:22.960
- God.

244
00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:26.240
How many do you need
for one weekend?

245
00:18:26.320 --> 00:18:29.120
- See ya later.

246
00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:33.480
- I can't.
- Tired?
- Nup.

247
00:18:34.360 --> 00:18:36.000
- Oh. Gidday.

248
00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
- Hey.
- How was town?

249
00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:43.360
- Uh. yeah. we. uh. had a drink
for Mitchell. Still can't quite
get our heads around it.

250
00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:45.280
- Understandable.
- Yeah.
- Big shock.

251
00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:47.440
You know what?

252
00:18:47.440 --> 00:18:51.120
Times like this. you need...
a distraction.

253
00:18:51.560 --> 00:18:54.880
Yeah. my wife and I.
this is―
a few years back ― we. uh...

254
00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:57.760
We did dancing lessons.
Rock 'n' roll.

255
00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:00.120
- Ha.
- Yeah. it was our respite.

256
00:19:00.120 --> 00:19:04.200
You know. when you're working hard
day and night. sometimes you just...

257
00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:06.400
You just forget to breathe.
- Yeah.

258
00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:08.520
You know. so twice a week.
we'd. um...

259
00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:12.040
Well. we'd hit the dancing studio.
and just whoo-hoo-hoo. daddy...

260
00:19:12.040 --> 00:19:14.920
- ...let the world disappear.
- Wow.

261
00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:17.120
I don't wanna be rude. but bye.

262
00:19:17.120 --> 00:19:19.120
Yeah. Yeah.

263
00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:22.960
- Vinny. Vinny. They're coming.

264
00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:25.600
Why didn't you stall them?

265
00:19:31.520 --> 00:19:35.520
- These people are mental.
- Devin said they used to be
police detectives.

266
00:19:35.520 --> 00:19:39.320
- That's so messed up.
- Try not to worry. Shay.

267
00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:42.720
- Gonna go have a shower.

268
00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:07.640
- Shh.

269
00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:16.080
- You climbed out the window.
- Yeah.

270
00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:20.320
- You could've just said
you were refreshing the towels.

271
00:20:20.320 --> 00:20:22.320
- You make a good point.

272
00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:28.280
- Next time I'll bring props.
- No next time.

273
00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:31.280
Can't be snooping around and get...

274
00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:35.400
You nicked the woman's make-up?
- She's got so much.
she won't even notice.

275
00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:37.320
I'll put it back after.

276
00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:41.640
- If we'd installed security
cameras. we'd know exactly who
was in Mitchell's room.

277
00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:44.080
- Way to kill the holiday vibe.

278
00:20:44.080 --> 00:20:45.760
We don't need cameras. Cole.

279
00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:52.440
Come on. Shaylah. I know you were
in Mitchell's hotel room that night.

280
00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:54.440
Oh. hey. We were just...

281
00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:57.760
trying to find a match
for the lipstick mark.

282
00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:01.760
- Jaffa Delight.
From the Main Beach Rd chemist.

283
00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:05.000
My ex used to wear it all the time.

284
00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:09.400
- Right. Well. I'm pretty sure your
ex didn't have a drink with Mitchell
in his motel room the night he died.

285
00:21:09.400 --> 00:21:12.000
- Yeah.
so it'll be old mate in Unit 2.

286
00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:16.000
- Maxine.
- Spotted it on her
the first second I saw her.

287
00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:19.160
- Gidday.
- Hello.

288
00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:22.400
- Hey. um. would you mind
answering a― a quick question?

289
00:21:22.400 --> 00:21:26.080
- I'm a open book. Mr Coleman.
- Did you know Mitchell Gould?

290
00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:28.680
- No. I didn't know him.
- Right.

291
00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:31.840
It's just that there are― there
are two wine glasses in every room.

292
00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:34.920
but there were three in Mitchell's
the morning after the night before.

293
00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:39.360
Do you. um― Do you have both
your wine glasses here. Maxine?
- Yeah. I do.

294
00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:44.040
And I'd like to get back to my
Jojo Moyes now. I'm on holiday.

295
00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:50.920
- She lied.
- Definitely.

296
00:21:51.520 --> 00:21:53.440
That's her wine glass.

297
00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:56.800
- Wanna know what else?
Maxine's check-in details.

298
00:21:56.800 --> 00:21:59.840
She's not from Auckland
like she says.

299
00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:03.440
- So where. then?
- Main Beach Rd. Mowai Bay.

300
00:22:04.280 --> 00:22:07.800
- So if she lives around the corner.
why is she staying at our motel?

301
00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:16.800
- Maxine?
- I'll go.
- No. no. I will.

302
00:22:16.800 --> 00:22:22.200
- I can.
- Shall we argue a bit longer and
make absolutely sure we lose her

303
00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:38.560
Hi. Um...

304
00:22:38.680 --> 00:22:43.720
I just saw my...
cousin coming out of here
shopping for our aunt's birthday.

305
00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:47.440
and. um... I don't wanna double up.
so can you tell me what
she purchased?

306
00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:50.840
- Well. what were you thinking
of getting your aunt?

307
00:22:50.840 --> 00:22:52.920
- Depends on what my cousin bought.

308
00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:57.520
- Well. we have this lovely room
spray. Is she a home scent person?

309
00:22:57.520 --> 00:23:00.920
- Can you just tell me?
- What kind of cousin?

310
00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:02.920
- Hmm?
- First cousins?

311
00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:09.240
- Did she buy wine glasses―
one ― one wine glass?

312
00:23:11.800 --> 00:23:13.800
I will buy a room spray.

313
00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:16.600
Will you tell me then?
- I am more inclined

314
00:23:16.600 --> 00:23:21.080
to make conversation with
paying customers. yes.
- Mm.

315
00:23:21.080 --> 00:23:22.200
- $70.

316
00:23:22.200 --> 00:23:23.440
- S―?
- Thank you.

317
00:23:25.920 --> 00:23:29.160
- My previous customer
purchased one wine glass.

318
00:23:29.160 --> 00:23:31.160
You're welcome.

319
00:23:38.800 --> 00:23:42.960
- Our wine glasses are a lot cheaper
than the ones at the gift store.
just FYI.

320
00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:46.280
- Oh. you know.
Andrea gets hers from the city
and hikes up the prices.

321
00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:50.160
She's shameless.
- Which you know. because...

322
00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:53.520
you're a local.

323
00:23:55.600 --> 00:23:57.600
- Yeah. OK.

324
00:23:59.040 --> 00:24:03.920
Uh... I have owned a holiday home
here for the last 22 years.

325
00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:09.480
And now that my husband's gone. I've
decided to live here permanently.
- I'm sorry for your loss.

326
00:24:09.480 --> 00:24:12.080
- Oh God. The prick didn't die.
He just left.

327
00:24:12.080 --> 00:24:14.120
Anyway. I have some leaks.
and they're getting fixed.

328
00:24:14.120 --> 00:24:19.520
and while they're getting fixed.
I've decided to stay at
your very lovely motel.

329
00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:23.280
- Why were you in Mitchell's room
the night he died?

330
00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:27.920
- Look. guys. Every―
Every New Year's Eve. this town is
filled to the brim with teenagers.

331
00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:30.600
They're drinking. they're partying.

332
00:24:30.600 --> 00:24:33.920
Years ago. Mitchell was
one of those teenagers.

333
00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:36.200
I met him... late one night.

334
00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:38.160
He was... 17.

335
00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:41.080
and I was a very youthful thirty...

336
00:24:41.080 --> 00:24:42.640
three.

337
00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:46.520
Anyways. he was stumbling on the
beach. He was drunk. he was crying.
he couldn't find hismates.

338
00:24:46.520 --> 00:24:48.840
so I took him home. fed him...

339
00:24:48.840 --> 00:24:51.640
He made a pass at me.
and then puked all over the patio.

340
00:24:51.640 --> 00:24:54.760
Hmm. Then his mates came
to pick him up the next day.

341
00:24:54.760 --> 00:24:58.360
He was bragging that
he'd scored himself a MILF.
- Mm. Charming.

342
00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:02.640
- Aw. I didn't really mind. Things
weren't going great with Barry.

343
00:25:02.640 --> 00:25:04.840
It was a nice little ego boost.

344
00:25:04.840 --> 00:25:06.840
- And two nights ago?

345
00:25:06.960 --> 00:25:12.240
- Well. when we saw each other.
he pretended not to recognise me.
I mean. he was even panicking.

346
00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:15.440
- You know why?
- Well. I had an inkling.

347
00:25:16.360 --> 00:25:19.400
Later that night. I stepped outside
for a menthol. and...

348
00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:21.880
there he was. Right next door.

349
00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:27.560
- Bludge one of those?

350
00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:30.600
- So I took my drink.
went to his room. had a chat.

351
00:25:30.600 --> 00:25:35.640
He just begged me not to let his
mates know that LF ―
and the rest.

352
00:25:35.640 --> 00:25:37.960
- He was worried about
a 20-year-old secret.

353
00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:40.040
- Well. you know these
alpha male types.

354
00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:45.280
If they knew their mate. the big
stud. had crashed in the spare room
and wee-weed on the bed...

355
00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:50.040
- OK. So...
you drink your wine. then leave.

356
00:25:50.040 --> 00:25:51.880
- Back to my unit to read.

357
00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:56.360
- His bottle of blue liqueur ―
did you see it in his room?

358
00:25:57.200 --> 00:25:59.640
- Did you. uh. steal that from
daddy's liquor cabinet. did you?

359
00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:03.640
- Yes. Great. great. great.
Very funny. Ha ha

360
00:26:04.200 --> 00:26:06.080
And thanks.

361
00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:08.080
That night...

362
00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:10.720
made me the legend I am today.

363
00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:15.880
Mitchell didn't deserve
what happened.

364
00:26:15.880 --> 00:26:19.080
Sometimes. these big-talking blokes.
they just...

365
00:26:19.080 --> 00:26:23.080
they're just insecure little boys
under it all.

366
00:26:26.160 --> 00:26:28.160
- Hi.
- Hi. Um...

367
00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:32.240
one of my make-up bags has
been stolen from our room.
- Oh.

368
00:26:32.240 --> 00:26:37.400
Oh. No.  saw
one of those in lost property.

369
00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:41.320
- Uh. how― how would it be
in lost property? I haven't
taken it anywhere.

370
00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:44.600
- Housekeeping must've gathered it
up with the towels.

371
00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:48.480
- What kind of incompetent staff―
- It's OK. babe.
There's no harm done.

372
00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:50.920
- Look. I know it's not easy
having to hang around.

373
00:26:50.920 --> 00:26:55.560
Police forensics will be back with
a toxicology report any minute now.

374
00:26:55.560 --> 00:26:58.760
- Good. Because this is insane.
- Ah...

375
00:26:59.120 --> 00:27:02.320
- Oh. Shaylah. Um...
Do you mind me asking ―

376
00:27:02.320 --> 00:27:04.480
did Mitchell ever hit on you?

377
00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:08.040
- Uh― sorry. I don't think
that's appropriate.

378
00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:11.800
- So that's the police angle.
- No. no. not police.
Just... curious.

379
00:27:11.800 --> 00:27:15.480
-  murdered every 40+ guy
who grabbed my arse.

380
00:27:15.480 --> 00:27:18.480
there would be
no one left in Ponsonby.
- Mitchell grabbed your arse?

381
00:27:18.480 --> 00:27:20.760
- I'm so over this shithole.

382
00:27:21.920 --> 00:27:26.120
- So...
Maxine knew Mitchell.
- Mm-hm.

383
00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:29.360
- But I can't find a logical motive.

384
00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:31.120
- Anything gone walkabout?

385
00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:33.720
If it was opportunistic.
someone could've grabbed
something from in here.

386
00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:35.800
- Yeah. Not that I can see.

387
00:27:35.800 --> 00:27:38.040
- Or it wasn't opportunistic.

388
00:27:38.040 --> 00:27:40.520
Maybe there was already beef.

389
00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:46.440
Come on. Cole. you're in this.
You wanna know as much as I do.

390
00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:48.800
- Fine. Come on.

391
00:27:49.760 --> 00:27:54.760
- Thanks for this. Jamie.
Just a quick look before
digital forensics do their thing.

392
00:27:54.760 --> 00:27:57.720
- It's allowed. Right?
- Totally. Yep. yep.
- Oh yeah. Absolutely.

393
00:27:57.720 --> 00:27:59.720
- OK.

394
00:28:00.760 --> 00:28:04.720
So... no mention of Shaylah
in recent emails.

395
00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:11.160
Ooh. Hang on. A week ago. Mitchell
sent Ross a big file of video.

396
00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:15.360
- No message?
- He's written 28.15.

397
00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:18.440
- Huh.

398
00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:22.640
Looks like a recording of
a livestream. A funeral.

399
00:28:22.640 --> 00:28:23.640
Tomo's?

400
00:28:23.640 --> 00:28:27.080
- We've lost the glue that...
holds us all together.

401
00:28:29.320 --> 00:28:33.560
- Tomo fought so hard. But...
he couldn't win in the end.

402
00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:35.360
- The timecode.
- Hmm?

403
00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:36.880
- The message that Mitchell wrote.

404
00:28:36.880 --> 00:28:40.360
28.15. It's referring to―
- The timecode.

405
00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:46.400
- OK. Pallbearers.

406
00:28:46.400 --> 00:28:48.400
Ross. Devlin.

407
00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:51.080
Random old gu―
- Oh.

408
00:28:51.080 --> 00:28:53.080
- Oh. Hold the bus.

409
00:28:53.320 --> 00:28:56.120
Different hair. but―

410
00:28:56.120 --> 00:28:57.880
- Shaylah.

411
00:28:57.880 --> 00:29:01.520
So much for only meeting Ross
and his mates three months ago.

412
00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:04.720
- So Mitchell sent this to Ross.
showing him that she was
at the funeral.

413
00:29:04.720 --> 00:29:06.880
- Looks like it.
- Oh. hang on.

414
00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:09.920
There's a 'Tomo' folder
on Mitchell's desktop.

415
00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:13.480
Car insurance. a bunch of paperwork
for Thomas Preble.

416
00:29:13.480 --> 00:29:15.920
- Did Mitchell have power
of attorney or something?

417
00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:17.920
- Oh. Cole.

418
00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:21.800
- Oh shit.
- Mm-hm.

419
00:29:22.280 --> 00:29:24.560
- Someone wanna share?
- OK.

420
00:29:24.560 --> 00:29:28.520
So about 10 years ago.
Cole decided to get life insurance.

421
00:29:28.520 --> 00:29:32.360
- After a close call at work.
- But they turned him down.
- Homicide detective.

422
00:29:32.360 --> 00:29:35.320
- Plus. he drank and
smoked like a chimney.
- OK. love.

423
00:29:35.320 --> 00:29:39.640
- Anyway. the point is.
they refused to give him cover
for life insurance.

424
00:29:39.640 --> 00:29:43.320
- And yet. Tomo here got a policy
even though he was...

425
00:29:43.320 --> 00:29:45.320
terminally ill.
- Hmm.

426
00:29:46.120 --> 00:29:49.360
- So he wasn't terminally ill
when he took the policy out.

427
00:29:49.360 --> 00:29:51.360
- Uh-uh.

428
00:29:52.440 --> 00:29:55.440
- OK. That's weird.
- Mm. You wanna know what's weirder?

429
00:29:55.440 --> 00:29:57.920
Look at the sole beneficiary.

430
00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:00.280
- Ross. How―?

431
00:30:00.280 --> 00:30:03.320
- You could probably cheat
the system if you had. say.

432
00:30:03.320 --> 00:30:05.920
a medical professional
willing to lie.

433
00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:08.400
- Mm. And Ross had one of those.

434
00:30:08.440 --> 00:30:10.440
His girlfriend.

435
00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:22.680
- Fresh towels.

436
00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:24.760
Oh. Um... one more thing.

437
00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:29.720
Can you tell me about
the life insurance policy
Ross's friend Tomo had?

438
00:30:29.720 --> 00:30:32.520
- Sorry?
- You don't know about it?

439
00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:36.400
- Why would  never met Tomo.
- Oh. Um. Tomo took out a policy.

440
00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:38.880
the sole beneficiary
being his mate Ross.

441
00:30:38.880 --> 00:30:42.680
- Get out.
- Insurance fraud
could be motive for murder

442
00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:44.680
if anyone found out.

443
00:30:44.760 --> 00:30:48.480
- How dare you.
- And so could falsifying
medical records.

444
00:30:48.480 --> 00:30:52.360
The cancer was advanced when he was
diagnosed. and yet he still got
a life insurance policy.

445
00:30:52.360 --> 00:30:54.560
- Hey. uh. what's going on?

446
00:30:54.760 --> 00:30:57.840
You OK. babe?
- No. She's saying that―

447
00:30:59.520 --> 00:31:01.920
I just need to get outta here.

448
00:31:02.800 --> 00:31:07.520
- Get our bill ready. We're leaving.
- Oh. you might wanna check
with Constable Haira first.

449
00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:10.800
- You're not the only motel
around here.

450
00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:22.720
- Shaylah and Ross didn't wanna
talk about his insurance fraud.

451
00:31:23.600 --> 00:31:27.880
Whatcha got there?
- Thought it was time for a break.

452
00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:30.880
- Mm. OK.

453
00:31:30.880 --> 00:31:32.880
Hmm.

454
00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:35.640
Look at us. Living the dream.

455
00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
- You sure?

456
00:31:41.840 --> 00:31:46.400
- Hmm?
- Oh. well. I've never seen you so
excited about a potential homicide.

457
00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:51.680
- Oh. you know me. If there's
a question. I wanna know the answer.

458
00:31:54.800 --> 00:31:56.800
Vin...

459
00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:01.160
You know you didn't have to...

460
00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:05.000
walk away. Right? If you feel like
you've made the wrong decision.

461
00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.040
- It was never a decision. Cole.

462
00:32:08.640 --> 00:32:10.640
Wherever you go. I go.

463
00:32:11.400 --> 00:32:13.400
No looking back.

464
00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:16.200
I love you.

465
00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:20.480
- You loved your career. too.

466
00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:24.600
- Hi. I'm Vinny Coleman.

467
00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:25.840
- Oh.
- I run a motel.

468
00:32:25.840 --> 00:32:27.840
- Oh.
- Yeah. And. um...

469
00:32:28.440 --> 00:32:31.240
I'm not letting you go ever again.

470
00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.800
Well...  back to reality.

471
00:32:48.760 --> 00:32:50.840
Back to the blocked sink.

472
00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:54.480
-  can't fix it tomorrow.
I'll call the plumber.

473
00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:57.120
An overpriced plumber who'll
probably charge an arm and a l―
- Hey!

474
00:32:57.120 --> 00:32:59.200
Litterbug!

475
00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:01.120
- Vin!

476
00:33:05.360 --> 00:33:09.320
- Get off! Get off!
What are you doing?

477
00:33:09.320 --> 00:33:10.720
- What did you throw
in the sea. Ross?

478
00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:12.920
- Why did you follow me
down to the beach?

479
00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:15.760
- We were here first.
- Well. I was just― you know.

480
00:33:15.760 --> 00:33:18.800
taking a walk!
- Was it a liqueur bottle?

481
00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:22.280
- You know. we aredefinitely
leaving tomorrow. And...

482
00:33:22.280 --> 00:33:26.880
And you're lucky I don't have you
charged with assault.

483
00:33:37.320 --> 00:33:40.520
- It was Ross.
Still didn't wanna talk.

484
00:33:41.960 --> 00:33:43.600
- What did you do?

485
00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:46.200
- Just... stopped him running.

486
00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:49.800
- Well. whatever he wanted
to get rid of has floated

487
00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:53.000
just out there past the waves.
You see?

488
00:33:53.280 --> 00:33:57.920
Or is that a bit of driftwood?
- According to Ross.
he threw nothing.

489
00:33:57.920 --> 00:33:59.920
- Well. who's gonna go get
this 'nothing'?

490
00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:02.440
- Well. I tackled him.

491
00:34:02.440 --> 00:34:05.040
S-Stopped him running. I mean.

492
00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:10.000
- What have I told you about
physically restraining motel guests?

493
00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:14.400
Hold that.

494
00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:21.120
- Can you tell us what it's about?
- It's OK. Shay.

495
00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:23.520
Just some more routine questions.
I'm sure.

496
00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:26.640
- OK. well. can you make it quick?
Cos we're moving motels today.

497
00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:30.240
- It's OK. darling.
Go pack. I won't be long.

498
00:34:37.680 --> 00:34:39.760
- Yeah. I'm still thinking
I should wait.

499
00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:42.840
- No way. He tried to dispose of
the murder weapon last night.

500
00:34:42.840 --> 00:34:45.640
- Yeah. but Detective Granger
from City Homicide ― she's on her
way. you know―

501
00:34:45.640 --> 00:34:47.880
- She's been on her way for days.
What is she. walking from Auckland?

502
00:34:47.880 --> 00:34:50.680
- Just see what Ross says
about throwing a liqueur bottle.

503
00:34:50.680 --> 00:34:54.360
He's looking terrified.
He might just fold.

504
00:34:57.360 --> 00:34:59.360
- Do you wanna sit in?

505
00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:04.360
That way if Detective Granger
kicks my arse. I can blame you.

506
00:35:15.400 --> 00:35:17.800
- Hey.
- Tox report came back.

507
00:35:18.160 --> 00:35:20.520
- And?
- And... nothing.

508
00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:25.320
Booze. Nicotine. That's it.
Maybe a medical event took him out.

509
00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:28.320
- One of those two was in
Mitchell's room the night of.

510
00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:32.560
One of them took the liqueur
bottle. Ross tossed it in the sea.
and you're concluding―

511
00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:34.960
I'm not concluding anything.

512
00:35:34.960 --> 00:35:37.440
We're detaining him until...

513
00:35:37.920 --> 00:35:39.400
something comes up.

514
00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:42.760
- Excuse me. love.
My sink's still not draining.

515
00:35:42.760 --> 00:35:45.760
- Cole?
- Yep. 'll pop back.

516
00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.000
- He's coming.

517
00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:40.280
- One. I stink.

518
00:36:40.560 --> 00:36:42.400
Two. I cleared the blockage
in the pipes.

519
00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:44.720
- Remember that time
you were giving up smoking

520
00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:47.200
and you didn't read the directions
on the patches properly.

521
00:36:47.200 --> 00:36:49.840
and you got―
- Nicotine poisoning.

522
00:36:49.840 --> 00:36:52.720
Yeah. I remember. Felt like death.

523
00:36:56.360 --> 00:37:00.440
You're pretty bloody good.
aren't you. Detective Coleman?
- I like to think so.

524
00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:05.520
And I'm always surprised at what
people think they can flush.

525
00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:08.120
- Oh ho ho.

526
00:37:08.120 --> 00:37:10.400
Oh yeah. We are bloody good.

527
00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.640
- And if you'd like to leave us
a Google review―

528
00:37:17.640 --> 00:37:19.640
- Are you joking?

529
00:37:19.680 --> 00:37:24.840
Here's my review. There's no
minibar. and the owners are freaks.

530
00:37:24.840 --> 00:37:30.120
-  know it's just
the nicotine withdrawals talking.

531
00:37:30.120 --> 00:37:33.280
You were attached to your vape
from the minute you got here.

532
00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:37.960
But after Mitchell died.
you appeared to go cold turkey.

533
00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:40.520
You didn't even take it
to the pub with you.

534
00:37:40.520 --> 00:37:44.320
- Cos I had no refills. And this
stupid-arse backwards town ran out.

535
00:37:44.320 --> 00:37:49.240
- Cole's an ex-smoker.
I know how organised you have to be
when you head out of town.

536
00:37:49.240 --> 00:37:52.840
But you were.
You had four refills with you.

537
00:37:53.960 --> 00:37:55.960
But where did they go?

538
00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:07.520
- Where's Ross? We wanna leave.
- Still at the station.

539
00:38:07.520 --> 00:38:09.720
- Ross has confessed
to killing Mitchell.

540
00:38:09.720 --> 00:38:11.720
- Really?
- What?

541
00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:15.240
But... What'd he say?
- He made a full statement.

542
00:38:15.240 --> 00:38:18.280
He laced Mitchell's bottle
with liquid nicotine and then
dropped him in the bath.

543
00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:21.200
Just to make sure.
And he flushed the capsules.

544
00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:24.240
- And he just offers this up
to a junior constable?

545
00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:28.120
He goes to all the trouble of
killing a man to keep his secret.
and then he just caves?

546
00:38:28.120 --> 00:38:32.680
- Ross will have to stay in custody
until we can get to court next week.
- No. this is bullshit.

547
00:38:32.680 --> 00:38:35.480
You must've coerced him or asked
leading questions or something.

548
00:38:35.480 --> 00:38:39.120
- No.  don't know
how to do that kind of thing yet.

549
00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:41.640
I'm new. so.
- We need a lawyer. His lawyer.

550
00:38:41.640 --> 00:38:44.440
- Ross called his lawyer already.

551
00:38:44.440 --> 00:38:46.440
- He wouldn't hurt a fly.

552
00:38:46.680 --> 00:38:49.880
He is the kindest.
best person I've ever met.

553
00:38:49.880 --> 00:38:52.560
OK? He didn't do it. He didn't...

554
00:38:53.520 --> 00:38:55.520
- Well.

555
00:38:55.520 --> 00:38:57.520
She's right.

556
00:38:57.800 --> 00:38:59.800
Because...

557
00:39:00.120 --> 00:39:02.120
you did it.

558
00:39:02.240 --> 00:39:04.240
That right. Shaylah?

559
00:39:06.240 --> 00:39:08.320
Mitchell had been drinking
that blue crap all afternoon.

560
00:39:08.320 --> 00:39:12.800
and you were on edge
because he had something over you.

561
00:39:13.200 --> 00:39:14.920
- What is it you see in him?

562
00:39:14.920 --> 00:39:19.120
- You and Ross.
And I'm guessing that this weekend.
he threatened to use it.

563
00:39:19.120 --> 00:39:23.040
So you went to Mitchell's room.
tried to change his mind...

564
00:39:23.040 --> 00:39:25.040
with an oldie but. uh...

565
00:39:25.040 --> 00:39:26.280
a goodie.

566
00:39:26.280 --> 00:39:29.280
But he wasn't making it easy
for you. was he. Shayla?

567
00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:31.560
He knew what you were up to.

568
00:39:31.560 --> 00:39:33.840
So in comes the backup plan.

569
00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.000
You had a go at his drink.

570
00:39:37.760 --> 00:39:39.800
Encouraged him to finish it.
You're a nurse.

571
00:39:39.800 --> 00:39:43.800
You know a high enough dose
of nicotine is fatal.

572
00:39:44.280 --> 00:39:48.080
He was crook.
Throwing up. feeling like shit.

573
00:40:04.920 --> 00:40:08.400
- Ross deserves everything
he's worked for.

574
00:40:08.400 --> 00:40:11.400
He was the only one
who visited Tomo.

575
00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:14.360
Only one who came to chemo.
supported him.

576
00:40:14.360 --> 00:40:17.360
- You were Tomo's nurse?
That's how you met Ross?

577
00:40:17.360 --> 00:40:22.480
- The others didn't give a shit.
And Tomo knew Ross just needed
some capital.

578
00:40:22.480 --> 00:40:26.360
It was his idea.
It was his parting gift to Ross.

579
00:40:26.400 --> 00:40:28.400
- It was very generous.

580
00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:31.560
Not sure the insurance company
he ripped off would agree.

581
00:40:31.560 --> 00:40:33.560
- I offered him money.

582
00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:39.400
Anything.
But he wanted to take Ross down
because he's spiteful and jealous.

583
00:40:39.400 --> 00:40:42.800
I said. 'Please just let us
get on with our lives.'

584
00:40:42.800 --> 00:40:45.280
But he wouldn't.
- Constable.

585
00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:49.640
Did you forget about me?
I've been waiting at the station.

586
00:40:49.640 --> 00:40:52.920
- But―
- He said he was going for a coffee.

587
00:40:53.080 --> 00:40:55.080
- But―
- Yeah. um...

588
00:40:55.080 --> 00:40:57.080
Ross didn't confess.

589
00:40:57.600 --> 00:41:00.280
- Sorry?
- Oh. you sneaky sneaks.

590
00:41:00.480 --> 00:41:02.480
- Really?

591
00:41:02.760 --> 00:41:04.560
- It was worth a crack.

592
00:41:04.560 --> 00:41:09.480
- The protocol handbook doesn't
say anything about bullshitting.

593
00:41:09.480 --> 00:41:11.880
But if it gets the job done...

594
00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:15.000
- Well played. you two.

595
00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:17.280
- Shay. for God's sakes ―
what's going on?

596
00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:19.720
- Come on. Ross.
You know what she did.
That's why you tossed the bottle.

597
00:41:19.720 --> 00:41:21.920
Cos you found it. what.
hidden in your room somewhere?

598
00:41:21.920 --> 00:41:26.280
- I thought it was a bad look.
I didn't think she'd actually
done anything.

599
00:41:26.280 --> 00:41:28.560
Darling.

600
00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:31.200
- I just hated him so much.
I'm sorry.

601
00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:34.400
He was just never gonna
leave us alone.

602
00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:39.960
- Shaylah. You're under arrest
for the murder of Mitchell Gould.

603
00:41:46.080 --> 00:41:49.760
- Don't worry. darling.
I'll call my lawyer.

604
00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:09.000
- She is a thing of beauty.
Isn't she?

605
00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:15.480
- We will get our rock 'n' roll
motel warming someday. I promise.

606
00:42:15.480 --> 00:42:17.480
- Yoohoo! Peter?

607
00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:21.400
Oh. hey.
Hey. just wondering what you guys
are planning to do with Unit 3.

608
00:42:21.400 --> 00:42:25.480
It's gonna be hard to fill
after the murder.
- Why do you ask?

609
00:42:25.480 --> 00:42:28.760
- Well. it's just that
my renovations are taking
longer than expected.

610
00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:33.040
so. look. I'm more than happy to
take the murder room off your hands
at a discount.

611
00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:35.040
You let me know.

612
00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:38.400
- I mean. a repeat guest...
who can argue with that?

613
00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:40.400
- Mm-hm.

614
00:42:42.400 --> 00:42:47.200
- Oh― Ooh. Interrupting.
- No. it's fine. Jamie.

615
00:42:47.200 --> 00:42:52.480
How is the homicide detective?
- Uh. pretty impressed. actually.

616
00:42:52.480 --> 00:42:54.960
Yeah. Are you sure I can't tell her
you guys helped me out?

617
00:42:54.960 --> 00:42:58.400
- No. no. We― We hate attention.
- Thank you.

618
00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:00.400
Uh...

619
00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:02.600
I almost felt like a real cop today.

620
00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:06.800
- Jamie. mate. lose the imposter
syndrome. You are a real cop.

621
00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:08.920
- Throw away the police
protocol handbook. you reckon?

622
00:43:08.920 --> 00:43:10.920
- Oh. I wouldn't do that.
- Mm... probably not.

623
00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:13.000
- OK. No.

624
00:43:13.280 --> 00:43:15.280
The thing is. I. um...

625
00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:19.320
I just gotta make this one stick.
you know?

626
00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:23.640
Well. like... when did you know
you wanted to be in the police?

627
00:43:23.640 --> 00:43:28.080
- Oh. when I was a little girl.
Yeah. It was never anything else.

628
00:43:28.080 --> 00:43:31.360
- See.  felt like that
about something.
- It's not a calling for you.

629
00:43:31.360 --> 00:43:35.400
- But could be.
Can get pretty addictive.

630
00:43:35.400 --> 00:43:38.280
- Anyway. uh... thanks.
- Any time.

631
00:43:38.920 --> 00:43:41.760
And hey. feel free
to call if you want.

632
00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:45.440
If anything comes up.
- Sure thing.
- Gotcha.

633
00:43:47.600 --> 00:43:51.080
OK. you were right ―
I do miss it just a little bit.
- Mm.

634
00:43:51.080 --> 00:43:55.560
- But there's no going back.
and I am... fine with that.

635
00:43:56.880 --> 00:43:58.880
- Well.

636
00:43:59.240 --> 00:44:01.080
Constable Haira calls.

637
00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:05.040
I don't suppose there's any problem
with giving him a hand?

638
00:44:05.040 --> 00:44:07.640
- Course. I mean. we probably
won't even hear from him again.

639
00:44:07.640 --> 00:44:09.640
- Nah. Probably not.

640
00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:17.640
Huh.

641
00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:20.840
Ooh.

642
00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:08.280
- Everyone in town calls you
Blue Murder Motel.
- Do they?

643
00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.600
- You hear about the guy
that blew himself up?
Karma's a beautiful thing.

644
00:45:12.600 --> 00:45:16.000
- Your victim. Gene ― he had
no fixed address. no next of kin.

645
00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.200
- Oh. hi. Won't be a second.

646
00:45:18.200 --> 00:45:21.680
- The old owners
never had this many guests.
- Well. we like guests. Saffron.

647
00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:23.080
That's―
- Oh.

648
00:45:23.080 --> 00:45:26.680
This wasn't―
- Probably wasn't
an accidental death.

649
00:45:26.680 --> 00:45:31.080
- I heard you two used to be
private investigators. Or still are?

650
00:45:31.080 --> 00:45:34.520
- Aargh!
- Honey. I thought we weren't
allowed to do that to guests.

651
00:45:35.305 --> 00:46:35.508
Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-
